english:
  title: A Letter to Uncle Suk-gang
  author: Shin Jong-ho
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The great wheel of creation never ceases to turn,
    As the years spin past like a cart's rotating hub.
    Yesterday I wrapped myself in layers of winter furs,
    This morning I have cut and sewn my spring garments.

    Before the bright window, holding up my mirror,
    I see my temples have turned white—
    While the peach blossoms above the wall
    Hold droplets fine as grains of millet.

    Gazing at this, sudden sorrow overtakes me,
    And my heart finds nowhere to rest.
    The golden belt already fastens my court robes,
    And wealth and honor satisfy—

    Yet I cannot decide whether to stay or go,
    Still clinging to the royal stipend.
    My humble cottage of eight or nine wooden frames
    Stands far off in the foothills of Mani Mountain.
    With rain cloak and straw cape,
    When I step from my door to the banks of clear rivers—

    When shall I cast off this office and depart,
    To walk forever in the company of pristine scenery?
  footnotes:
    - 'Mani Mountain (摩尼麓): A sacred mountain, symbolizing a place of retirement and spiritual refuge.'
    - 'The golden belt and court robes: Symbols of official rank and the constraints of court service.'
